A passionate advocate for LGBTQ+ rights and representation in media.

Emilio Sandoval started acting at thirteen but made headlines at sixteen when he divorced his parents after discovering they had stolen his earnings. The widely publicized case brought him national attention. Later, a casting director told him he wasn't any good - and he agreed. Emilio took a break from acting to study workshops, classes, and community theater before returning to indie films at twenty-four. He credits that casting director's brutal honesty for his eventual success. Born in Oaxaca, Emilio has become a household name across Mexican and South American cinema since his 1979 professional debut. From 2022 to 2025, he starred in commercials for Casino Dorado Azteca that became cultural phenomena. His career spans Mexican, South American, and US productions.

Mateo Quiroga competed as a sumo wrestler in Tokyo from 2018 to 2020, fighting under the name Aguila del Sol and retiring with a 14-3 record. Originally from Aguascalientes, he got his first taste of acting through Japanese television commercials for shampoo and mouthwash that featured him as the gentle giant character. When he returned to Mexico, his celebrity status from sumo helped him land his first acting roles in 2021. Lucha Libre Occidental offered him a contract in 2022 to become a professional luchador, but nagging injuries from his sumo days forced him to decline. Mateo discovered sumo during a cultural exchange program at Universidad Autónoma de Aguascalientes, where a visiting Japanese coach spotted his natural build and invited him to train in Tokyo.

Araceli Lizarraga was eight when her mother died, leaving her to help her father raise four younger siblings in Tuxtla Gutiérrez. By fifteen, she could change diapers, pack school lunches, and mediate fights between her brothers with the efficiency of a seasoned parent. In 2020, she got caught up in a massive scandal involving the prank channel Bromas Sin Límites when she and two others faked a kidnapping in broad daylight. No charges were filed against Araceli, but the production company faced heavy fines. The controversy boosted her profile in Mexican cinema for all the wrong reasons. She issued a heartfelt apology video that she insists was genuine. Her acting career began in 2017 and somehow flourished despite the scandal, proving that sometimes bad publicity really is better than no publicity.

Luke Osmont started his acting career in his hometown of Bamberg in 2023. In 2024, he attended a workshop with German film legend Ben Kranzel and afterward asked him for a role in an upcoming film. When Kranzel politely declined, citing Luke's inexperience, Luke became aggressive and shoved him before being removed by security. Kranzel chose not to press charges. The incident became public knowledge in German film circles. Luke took controversial roles afterward, hoping to generate positive attention within the industry. He moved from Bamberg to Berlin, taking any part offered to him regardless of the project's quality or reputation. His performances have received mixed reactions from critics and audiences alike.

Hazel Kruger was born in Heidelberg and was a standout athlete through high school and at Friedrich-Schiller-Universität. She competed on the obstacle course competition Deutschland Hindernislauf Champions in 2020 and 2021, coming in second place both times after dominating early rounds. Originally planning to work as a stunt performer, Hazel was convinced by her older sister Molly to try acting at twenty. Molly insisted Hazel's big personality and talent for creative storytelling - particularly her elaborate lies to get out of trouble with their parents - would translate perfectly to screen work. Hazel made her acting debut in 2016 and has since balanced both stunt work and acting roles. Her athletic background gives her a natural advantage in action sequences and physically demanding performances.

Hagen Strickner worked as a lounge singer in Munich before transitioning to acting in 2005. He's been married four times and has also done modeling since 1999. In 2019, he became embroiled in a scandal involving the planned nightclub "Goldener Löwe" in Berlin. Investors claimed the club was never built despite receiving funding, while Hagen maintained he was only hired as a planner and entertainer, not the project manager. His very public 2020 divorce from politician Ingrid Metz made headlines when he was accused of having an affair with actress Ursula Strauss. The combination of the nightclub controversy and messy divorce dominated German tabloids for months. Hagen has navigated these scandals while maintaining his entertainment career across multiple decades.

Jens Weileroth from Cologne, Germany started acting in 2007 while still competing in professional wrestling and boxing. His wrestling career ended in 2020, while his boxing career concluded dramatically in 2023 when he knocked out longtime rival Pierre Dubois in just fifteen seconds of the first round. Despite his intimidating appearance, Jens has volunteered extensively at children's hospitals throughout his career. He bought his parents, Klaus and Wolfgang, a house as gratitude for raising him. Jens describes himself as having been a problem child, though his parents disagree with that assessment. Now that his boxing career is over, he's focusing entirely on acting for the first time in his life.

Angie Barnam started acting in 2025 after careers in professional wrestling and roller derby in Missoula, Montana. She's also an avid bodybuilder who made headlines in the Missoula Mountain Times when she lifted a Volkswagen Beetle off the ground from the rear and held it for forty-three seconds during a strongman exhibition. Angie loves camping alone in the wilderness around Glacier National Park, often disappearing for days with just a backpack and sleeping bag. She's notorious in roller derby circles for keeping track of how many teeth she's knocked out during matches - currently sitting at seventeen. In wrestling, she performed under the ring name "Kassie Kaos," a persona that was an amplified version of herself that allowed her to be loud and wild when she's more reserved in real life.

Ashley Karter started acting in 2024 after participating in theater at Lincoln Valley High School and begging to join community theater in Cedar Falls, Iowa, even offering to work as an unpaid extra. She felt local colleges lacked strong theater programs, so she jumped straight into professional acting instead of pursuing higher education. Ashley discovered her love for performance during a childhood accident when she fell through the rotting floorboards of her family's old barn and found a hidden room filled with vintage circus costumes and props from the 1920s. Her great-uncle had apparently been a traveling carnival performer who stored his equipment there before disappearing. Ashley spent summers teaching herself juggling, stilt-walking, and acrobatics using the dusty equipment she found buried beneath decades of forgotten memories.

Josef was the name he was born with. His uncle Adnan raised him like a second father and was the person he admired most. In 2003, an airstrike leveled Adnan’s apartment and killed him. Two years later, Josef legally took his uncle’s name and became Adnan Al-Omari. At the time, he was a pilot in the Palestinian air force, flying missions while secretly taking acting classes. He convinced his commanders to let his coaches visit the base, and soon formed an acting troupe with fellow soldiers. He made his film debut in 2005. Quiet and disciplined, Adnan keeps a strict routine and rarely speaks publicly. Every role he plays is a way to keep his uncle’s memory alive.

Nour Khalil once called herself a great liar, which is how she explains her love for acting. She joined the Palestinian military to escape her grief after losing both parents in the same bombing that killed Adnan Al-Omari’s uncle. On base, she found purpose again through the acting troupe Wings of Stone, where she and Adnan performed between missions. She also became an undefeated flyweight boxer, finishing with a record of 34 wins and no losses. Standing six feet tall with a stern look that scares most people off, Nour is all heart behind the scenes. She loves making her friends laugh and plays the role of proud aunt to her nieces and nephews. Hide and seek, she says, isn’t easy when you’re the tallest person in the house.

Oceane Proussard was born two minutes before her fraternal twin sister Macie, who became a composer and avoids the spotlight. They were raised in the small city of Cahors by their mothers, Claire and Élodie. While Macie followed music, Oceane was drawn to performance. She stood out early at Lycée Émile Charvet, a competitive arts-focused high school, and later at the Conservatoire de l’Image et des Sciences Sociales, where she double majored in theater and criminology. Her acting debut came in 2016 through a string of low budget French films. When she’s not working, she still reads about real cases and criminal theory, as it is her second passion.

Pablo San Luiz grew up in Mexico City as the middle child of five siblings in a family that ran Casa Verde, a small restaurant near Universidad Benito Juárez. His parents expected all their children to help with the business, but Pablo was more interested in the stories customers told than taking their orders. He started writing plays in high school at Instituto Cultural San Miguel, casting his classmates in productions they'd perform in the restaurant's back room on weekends. After graduating, he studied theater at Centro de Artes Dramáticas in Mexico City and made his acting debut in 2014 in a low-budget independent film. Pablo has a photographic memory for dialogue and can recite entire scripts after reading them twice.
Kirsten Schreiber is a talented actor known for her versatility and strong performances in both film and television.
